[[Category:Lists of the vascular plants of the British Isles|03]]

{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}} [[File:TCstaterainfall.gif|right|thumb|450px|Continental U.S. tropical cyclone rainfall maxima per state as of 2018|alt=Map showing the highest rainfall totals measured in certain regions of the continental United States as of 2018.]] [[Tropical cyclone]]s move into the [[contiguous United States]] from the [[Atlantic Ocean]], the [[Gulf of Mexico]], and the eastern [[Pacific Ocean]]. The highest rainfall totals in the country have been measured across the [[Gulf Coast of the United States|Gulf Coast]] and lower portions of the [[East Coast of the United States|Eastern Seaboard]]. Intermediate amounts have been measured across the [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]], [[New England]], and the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]]. The northern [[Great Plains]] and [[Northwestern United States|Pacific Northwest]] have received the lowest amounts, as those regions lie exceptionally far from the [[tropical cyclogenesis|breeding grounds]] of [[North Atlantic tropical cyclone|Atlantic]] and [[Pacific hurricane|Eastern Pacific tropical cyclones]].
A measurement of {{convert|60.58|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rain during [[Hurricane Harvey]], in Southeast Texas, holds the record for the highest precipitation total observed with a tropical cyclone in the United States. [[Tropical Storm Claudette (1979)|Tropical Storm Claudette]] holds the national 24-hour rainfall record, recorded in Alvin, Texas with {{convert|42.00|in|mm|abbr=on}} observed within such a timeframe. Taking place only one year apart, in 1978 and 1979, tropical storms [[Tropical Storm Amelia (1978)|Amelia]] and Claudette are also among the wettest tropical cyclones on record in the United States and they both have occurred in [[Texas]]. Hurricanes [[Hurricane Hiki|Hiki]] and [[Hurricane Lane (2018)|Lane]] both dumped significant rainfall in the mountains of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]], each with approximately {{convert|52.00|in|mm|abbr=on}} of rainfall reported.
==Overall wettest== [[File:Precipitation in Nederland, TX in 2017.svg|thumb|right|250px|Precipitation in Nederland, TX in 2017]] Below is a list of the top ten highest storm total rainfall amounts from individual tropical cyclones across the United States since 1950, including territories. {| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=in the United States}} |- | 1 || 1538.7 || 60.58 || [[Hurricane Harvey|Harvey 2017]] || [[Nederland, Texas]] ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 2 || 1321 || 52.02 || [[Hurricane Lane (2018)|Lane 2018]] || Mountainview, Hawaii ||<ref>{{cite report |title=Hawaii 72 hour archive of the RR5HFO summary |url=http://www.prh.noaa.gov/hnl/pages/RR5_archive.php |website=National Weather Service |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=26 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |last1=Kodama |title=NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE HONOLULU HI |url=https://nwschat.weather.gov/p.php?pid=201808252342-PHFO-NOHW40-PNSHFO |website=National Weather Service |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |accessdate=26 August 2018}}</ref> |- | 3 || 1321 || 52.00 || [[Hurricane Hiki|Hiki 1950]] || Kanalohuluhulu Ranger Station, Hawaii ||<ref name="C1950">{{cite report|author=Central Pacific Hurricane Center|url=http://www.prh.noaa.gov/cphc/summaries/1900-52.php|title=Tropical Cyclones During the Years 1900-1952|accessdate=January 26, 2007|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service}}</ref> |- | 4 || 1219 || 48.00 || [[Tropical Storm Amelia (1978)|Amelia 1978]] || Medina, Texas ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 5 || 1148 || 45.20 || [[Hurricane Easy (1950)|Easy 1950]] || Yankeetown, Florida ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 6 || 1143 || 45.00 || [[Tropical Storm Claudette (1979)|Claudette 1979]] || Alvin, Texas ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 7 || 1058.7 || 41.68 || [[Tropical Depression Fifteen (1970)|T. D. #15 1970]] || Jayuya, Puerto Rico ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 8 || 1033 || 40.68 || [[Tropical Storm Allison|Allison 2001]] || Northwest Jefferson County, Texas ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 9 || 985 || 38.76 || [[Tropical Storm Paul (2000)|Paul 2000]] || Kapapala Ranch 36, Hawaii ||<ref name="HPC Paul 2000">{{cite book|author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/paul2000filledrainblk.gif|accessdate=December 28, 2007|format=GIF|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|chapter=Remains of Paul|author=Roth, David M.|title=Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima}}</ref> |- | 10 || 977 || 38.46 || [[Hurricane Georges|Georges 1998]] || Munson, Florida ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |}
==Overall wettest in the contiguous United States== Below is a list of the top ten highest storm total rainfall amounts from individual tropical cyclones across the contiguous United States since 1950. The remains of [[Tropical Storm Amelia (1978)|Amelia 1978]] led to the wettest storm total rainfall amounts of any tropical cyclone to impact the lower 48 over that time frame when it moved into Texas during early August 1978.<ref name="WPCMAX"/> It would not be surpassed until [[Hurricane Harvey]] in 2017, which dropped a maximum of 60.58&nbsp;inches (1538.7&nbsp;mm), making it the wettest tropical cyclone in the United States.<ref name="WPCMAX"/> [[File:Allison Flood Houston.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Flooding due to Allison in Houston, TX in 2001]] {| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=on the United States Mainland}} |- | 1 || 1538.7 || 60.58 || [[Hurricane Harvey|Harvey 2017]] || [[Nederland, Texas]] ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 2 || 1219 || 48.00 || [[Tropical Storm Amelia (1978)|Amelia 1978]] ||Medina, Texas ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 3 || 1148 || 45.20 || [[Hurricane Easy (1950)|Easy 1950]] || Yankeetown, Florida ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 4 || 1143 || 45.00 || [[Tropical Storm Claudette (1979)|Claudette 1979]] || Alvin, Texas ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 5 || 1033 || 40.68 || [[Tropical Storm Allison|Allison 2001]] || Northwest Jefferson County, Texas ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 6 || 977 || 38.46 || [[Hurricane Georges|Georges 1998]] || Munson, Florida ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 7 || 932.4 || 36.71 || [[Hurricane Danny (1997)|Danny 1997]] || [[Dauphin Island, Alabama|Dauphin Island]] Sea Lab, Alabama ||{{Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima}}<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 8 || 912.6 || 35.93 || [[Hurricane Florence (2018)|Florence 2018]] || [[Elizabethtown, North Carolina]] ||<ref name="preliminary totals for Florence">{{cite web|url=https://ktvq.com/news/trending/2018/09/20/major-preliminary-rainfall-totals-for-hurricane-florence/|title=Major preliminary rainfall totals for Hurricane Florence|author=Connor Pregizer|publisher=KTVQ Billings News|date=20 September 2018|accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref> |- | 9 || 756 || 29.76 || [[1960 Texas tropical storm|Unnamed 1960]] || Port Lavaca #2, Texas ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 10 || 731 || 28.78 || [[Tropical Storm Debby (2012)|Debby 2012]] || Curtis Mill, Florida ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |} {{clear}}
==Alabama== The wettest tropical cyclone to impact the state of [[Alabama]] was [[Hurricane Danny (1997)|Hurricane Danny]], which stalled over [[Mobile Bay]] for over 24&nbsp;hours, and which led to significant rainfall.<ref>{{cite book|accessdate=June 9, 2012|author=Roth, David M|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/danny1997.html|title=Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima|chapter=Hurricane Danny Rainfall Page|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center}}</ref>
