==Alaska== No tropical cyclone has ever affected Alaska, but extratropical remnants of tropical cyclones have been known to bring heavy rainfall to the state. Examples include the extratropical remnants of [[Hurricane Fico]] in 1978.<ref name="CPHC 1978">{{cite report|url=http://www.prh.noaa.gov/cphc/summaries/1978.php|title=The 1978 Central Pacific Tropical Cyclone Season|author=Central Pacific Hurricane Center|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref>
==American Samoa== [[Image:Tropical Cyclone Heta 2004.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|Cyclone Heta (2004)]] Tropical cyclones impact the island chain with tropical storm-force winds once every three years, on average.<ref>{{cite web|author=Astrid Sesega|url=http://www.samoalivenews.com/Health/Cyclone-Fears-High-In-Samoa.html|title=Cyclone Fears High In Samoa|accessdate=March 7, 2008}}</ref> The wettest known cyclone to affect the island group occurred early in 1966, when nearly {{convert|19|in|mm}} fell at Vaipito.<ref name="WPCMAX"/>
{{Wettest tropical cyclones in American Samoa|align=left}} {{clear}}
==Arizona== [[Hurricane Nora (1997)|Hurricane Nora]] was the last tropical cyclone to enter the [[United States]] from [[Mexico]] at tropical storm strength.<ref>{{cite report|author=Rappaport, Edward N |type=Preliminary Report |url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/1997nora.html |title=Hurricane Nora 1997 |accessdate=March 4, 2008 |author2=National Hurricane Center |publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050925163209/http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/1997nora.html |archivedate=September 25, 2005 |df= }}</ref> The rainfall which fell across the [[Harquahala Mountains]] led to the state's 24-hour rainfall record.<ref name="top Arizona tc events">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrh.noaa.gov/psr/tropics/hurricanes.htm|title=...Top Arizona Hurricane/Tropical Storm Events..|accessdate=December 30, 2007}}</ref> [[Image:Hurricane Nora Remnants 1997.JPG|thumb|right|250 px|A weakening Tropical Storm Nora over Arizona on September&nbsp;23, 1997]]
{{Wettest tropical cyclones in Arizona|align=left}} {{Clear}}
==Arkansas== [[Tropical Storm Allison (1989)|Tropical Storm Allison in 1989]] stalled for three days across southeast Texas which led to prolonged rains across Arkansas. This way, Allison became the wettest known tropical cyclone to impact the state.<ref>{{cite report|author=Case, Robert Allen|author2=National Hurricane Center|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1989-prelim/allison/|title=Tropical Storm Allison|type=Preliminary Report|page=2|format=GIF|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> [[File:Allison 1989-06-26 1800Z.png|thumb|right|250 px|Tropical Storm Allison (1989)]]
