pical Cyclone Harvey Advisory Number 53|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> |- | 9 || 248.9 || 9.80 || [[1942 Atlantic hurricane season#Hurricane Two|Hurricane One, 1942]] || Springbank ||<ref name="Rain pre 50s"/> |- | 10 || 246.9 || 9.72 || [[1973 Atlantic hurricane season#Tropical Storm Delia|Delia 1973]] || Jessieville ||<ref name="WPCGULF"/> |}
==California== One of five known eastern Pacific tropical cyclones to bring tropical storm-force winds to the Southwest,<ref>{{cite journal|author2=Landsea, Christopher W|doi=10.1175/BAMS-85-11-1689|author=Chenoweth, Michael|url=http://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/pdf/10.1175/BAMS-85-11-1689|archiveurl=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/Landsea/chenowethlandsea.pdf|publisher=American Meteorological Society|title=The San Diego Hurricane of October 2, 1858|accessdate=June 4, 2012|journal=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|archivedate=December 8, 2004|deadurl=no|format=PDF|year=2004|volume=85|issue=11|pages=1689|bibcode = 2004BAMS...85.1689C }}</ref> Hurricane Kathleen accelerated northward ahead of an upper level trough, spreading heavy rains into the transverse ranges of southern [[California]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/kathleen1976.html|title=Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima|chapter=Hurricane Kathleen Rainfall Page|author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|author=Roth, David M|date=March 8, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> [[File:Hurricane Olivia Sep 21 1982 1830Z.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|Hurricane Olivia (1982)]]
