==Colorado== Few tropical cyclone remnants originating from the eastern Pacific make it as far north as [[Colorado]]. [[Hurricane Javier (2004)|Javier]] dropped locally heavy rainfall exceeding {{convert|4|in|mm}} over the higher terrain of western Colorado in 2004.<ref name="Western"/> [[Image:Hurricane Lester 22 aug 1992 2246Z.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|Hurricane Lester (1992)]] {| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=in Colorado}} |- | 1 || 135.9 || 5.35 || [[Hurricane Lester (1992)|Lester 1992]] || Wolf Creek Pass 1 E ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 2 || 109.2 || 4.30 || [[Hurricane Javier (2004)|Javier 2004]] || Beartown ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 3 || 68.6 || 2.70 || [[Hurricane Blanca (2015)|Blanca 2015]] || Paonia 15 NW ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 4 || 48.3 || 1.90 || [[Hurricane Dolly (2008)|Dolly 2008]] || Her ||<ref name="Western"/> |- |} {{clear}}
==Connecticut== While [[Hurricane Diane]] is wettest known tropical cyclone to impact [[New England]], the [[1938 New England hurricane]] produced the most rain in the state of Connecticut.<ref name="WPCMAX"/> Nonetheless, the flood from [[Hurricane Diane]] led to a significant death toll (nearly 200) from Pennsylvania eastward through southern New England.<ref name="Diane">{{cite book|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/diane1955.html|author=Roth, David M|title=Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima|chapter=Hurricane Diane Rainfall Page|date=March 4, 2008|author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|accessdate=March 4, 2008}}</ref> [[File:EloiseSeptember2219751700UTC.png|thumb|right|250px|Hurricane Eloise (1975)]]
