==Georgia== [[Tropical Storm Alberto (1994)|Tropical Storm Alberto in 1994]] looped across central Georgia, leading to 24-hour rainfall amounts exceeding {{convert|20|in|mm}} across central sections of the state.<ref name="Alberto">{{cite book|author=Roth, David M|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|title=Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima|author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/alberto1994.html|chapter=Tropical Storm Alberto Rainfall Page|accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> It also became the wettest tropical cyclone on record for the state of Georgia, eclipsing the record set in 1929.<ref name="WH">{{cite journal|author1=Haggard, William H|author2=Bilton, Thaddeus H|author3=Crutcher, Harold L|url=http://ams.allenpress.com/archive/1520-0450/12/1/pdf/i1520-0450-12-1-50.pdf|format=PDF|title=Maximum Rainfall from Tropical Cyclone Systems which Cross the Appalachians|accessdate=July 16, 2007|journal=Journal of Applied Meteorology|volume=12|pages=50–61|doi=10.1175/1520-0450(1973)012<0050:MRFTCS>2.0.CO;2|bibcode = 1973JApMe..12...50H |year=1973}}</ref>
