==Guam== [[Typhoon Pamela (1976)|Super Typhoon Pamela]] was not only a wet tropical cyclone for the island of Guam, but a destructive one as well. Since Pamela, wooden structures across Guam have been largely replaced by concrete structures in order to better weather typhoons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rms.com/catastrophe/models/Guam.asp |work=Risk Management Solutions |title=Guam Catastrophe Model |accessdate=June 16, 2007 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207111227/http://www.rms.com/catastrophe/models/Guam.asp |archivedate=February 7, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pacificworlds.com/guam/land/winds.cfm |title=Winds |work=PacificWorlds.com |accessdate=June 16, 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070827132157/http://www.pacificworlds.com/guam/land/winds.cfm |archivedate=August 27, 2007 |df= }}</ref> [[Image:Typhoon Pongsona (2002).JPG|thumb|right|250 px|Typhoon Pongsona (2002)]]
{{Wettest tropical cyclones in Guam|align=left}} {{clear}}
==Hawaii== [[File:Lane_2018-08-21_2350Z.jpg|thumb|right|Hurricane Lane (2018)]] This island state frequently sees rainfall from the remains of former eastern and central Pacific tropical cyclones. However, despite Hawaii's location in the subtropics, direct impacts by tropical cyclones are infrequent due to the protective influence of the Central Pacific Tropical Upper Tropospheric Trough (TUTT), which normally dissipates systems approaching Hawaii. Hurricane Hiki in 1950 led to significant rainfall in the mountains, with {{convert|52|in|mm}} of rainfall reported.<ref name="C1950"/> This was the most rainfall reported to have been produced by a tropical cyclone within the United States until surpassed by Hurricane Harvey in 2017.<ref name="WPCMAX"/> {{Wettest tropical cyclones in Hawaii|align=left}}
{{clear}}
==Idaho== Impacts from tropical cyclones in the [[Pacific Northwest]] are rare. Most recently, the remains of [[1982 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Olivia|Olivia]] moved through the region in 1982, spurring spotty moderate to heavy rainfall across [[Idaho]].<ref name="Western"/> [[Image:hurricaneoliviavis.GIF|thumb|right|250 px|Olivia (1982)]]
