==Louisiana== Heavy rains and flooding are the primary problem associated with tropical cyclones across the Pelican State. Recent examples of flooding across the state from tropical cyclones include [[Tropical Storm Allison]] in 2001, [[Tropical Storm Frances (1998)|Tropical Storm Frances]] in 1998, [[Tropical Storm Allison (1989)|Tropical Storm Allison]] in 1989, and [[Tropical Storm Claudette (1979)|Tropical Storm Claudette]] in 1979. Three of the four systems stalled across eastern Texas, prolonging the rainfall which occurred over [[Louisiana]]. If it were not for the intermittent invasions from tropical cyclones, rainfall during the months of August, September, and October would average about 25% less than it currently does.<ref>{{cite web |author=Roth, David M |url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/lahur.pdf |title=A Brief Climatology of Tropical Cyclones in Louisiana |publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service |author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center |accessdate=June 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68CeuGiEc?url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/lahur.pdf |archivedate=June 5, 2012 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>
