==Maine== The combined impact from a [[Nor'easter]] just one day before Daisy hit, and Hurricane Daisy, caused severe flooding in [[Maine]], when rain fell for 65&nbsp;consecutive hours in some locations. Rainfall from the two systems caused record rainfall in some areas in Maine.<ref name="disc2">{{cite report|author=Sable, Edward Sable|title=Hurricane Daisy effects on New England|type=United States Government Memorandum|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|accessdate=June 5, 2012|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/storm_wallets/atlantic/atl1962/daisy/preloc/bos1123b.gif|author2=United States Weather Bureau|date=November 23, 1962}}</ref><ref name="1962 MWR">{{cite journal|author=Dunn, Gordan E and staff|title=The hurricane season of 1962|journal=Monthly Weather Review|publisher=American Meteorological Society|accessdate=June 5, 2012|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/lib1/nhclib/mwreviews/1962.pdf|format=PDF|doi=10.1175/1520-0493-91.4.199|year=1963|volume=91|issue=4|pages=199|bibcode = 1963MWRv...91..199D }}</ref> Flooding caused by [[Hurricane Irene]]'s heavy rainfall washed out two bridges on [[Maine State Route 27|State Route 27]] in [[Carrabassett Valley, Maine|Carrabassett Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunjournal.com/franklin/story/1080326|title=Carrabassett Valley deals with aftermath of Hurricane Irene|last=Bryant|first=Ann|date=August 30, 2011|publisher=[[Sun Journal (Lewiston)|Sun Journal]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref>
[[Image:Hurricane irene 082811 0832 edt.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|Hurricane Irene]]
