==Mississippi== [[Hurricane Georges]] stalled over the southern portion of the state, it produced torrential rainfall, exceeding {{convert|30|in|mm}} locally.<ref name="GEO">{{cite book|author=Roth, David M|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/georges1998.html|title=Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima|chapter=Hurricane Georges Rainfall Page|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> The heavy rainfall contributed to significant river overflowing, including the Tchoutacabouffa River at [[D'Iberville, Mississippi|D'Iberville]], which set a record crest of {{convert|19|ft|m}}.<ref name="Georges TCR">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/1998georges.html |title=Hurricane Georges 1998 |author=Guiney, John L |author2=National Hurricane Center |date=January 5, 1999 |publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service |accessdate=June 3, 2012 |format=Preliminary Report |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005024537/http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/1998georges.html |archivedate=October 5, 2009 |df= }}</ref> [[File:Hurricane Georges 28 sept 1998 2043Z.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Hurricane Georges (1998)]]
