==North Carolina== [[File:Florence 2018-09-13 1550Z.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Hurricane Florence]] Heavy rains accompany [[tropical cyclones]] and their remnants which move northeast from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] coastline, as well as inland from the western subtropical [[Atlantic ocean]]. As much as 15% of the rainfall which occurs during the warm season in the Carolinas is attributable to tropical cyclones.<ref>{{cite web|author=Knight, David B |author2=Davis, Robert E |url=http://bellwether.metapress.com/content/n562284522t561n5/ |title=Climatology of Tropical Cyclone Rainfall in the Southeastern United States |accessdate=June 5, 2012 |doi=10.2747/0272-3646.28.2.126 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120709061001/http://bellwether.metapress.com/content/n562284522t561n5/ |archivedate=July 9, 2012 |df= }}</ref> Over the past 30&nbsp;years, the wettest tropical cyclone to strike the coastal plain was [[Hurricane Florence]] of September 2018, which dropped over {{convert|30|in|mm}} of rainfall in [[Swansboro, North Carolina|Swansboro]]. In the mountains, [[Hurricane Frances]] of September 2004 was the wettest, bringing over {{convert|23|in|mm}} of rainfall to [[Mount Mitchell]].<ref name="WPCSE"/>
