==North Dakota== It is rare for tropical cyclone remnants originating from the eastern Pacific or Atlantic Basins to migrate as far north as [[North Dakota]]. The remains of [[Hurricane Javier (2004)|Javier in 2004]] dropped locally heavy rainfall exceeding {{convert|1|in|mm}} in localized spots.<ref name="Mid West"/> [[Image:Hurricane javier 2004.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Hurricane Javier (2004)]]
{| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=in North Dakota}} |- | 1 || 34.0 || 1.34 || [[Hurricane Javier (2004)|Javier 2004]] || Homme Dam ||<ref name="Mid West"/> |- |} {{clear}}
==Northern Mariana Islands== [[Image:Champi 2015-10-16 0055Z.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|Typhoon Champi (2015)]] The [[Northern Mariana Islands]] are an archipelago north of Guam which gets impacted by typhoons in the western Pacific from time to time. [[2015 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Champi|Typhoon Champi]] dropped {{convert|26.25|in|mm}} on Tinian in 2015,<ref name="champi"/> making it the wettest known tropical cyclone for the island chain.
{{Wettest tropical cyclones in the Northern Marianas Islands|align=left}} {{Clear}}
==Ohio== The state of [[Ohio]] can be impacted by the remnants of both eastern Pacific and Atlantic tropical cyclones, with a bulk of the activity originating in the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. [[Hurricane Frederic]] in 1979, interacting with a nearby frontal zone,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[National Weather Service]]|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/dwm/data_rescue_daily_weather_maps.html|title=Daily Weather Maps: September 10–16, 1979|accessdate=March 6, 2008}}</ref> brought over {{convert|8|in|mm}} of rainfall to isolated spots of the state, becoming the wettest known tropical cyclone, or remnant, to impact Ohio.<ref name="Mid West"/> [[File:Frederic September 12 1979 1645Z.png|thumb|right|250 px|Hurricane Frederic (1979)]]
