==Texas== [[File:Harvey 2017-08-25 2231Z.png|thumb|right|200px|upright=1.5|Hurricane Harvey (2017)]] The most serious threat from tropical cyclones in Texas residents is from flooding, from both Gulf of Mexico hurricanes and tropical storms and the remnants of Eastern Pacific storms. Systems with sprawling circulations, such as [[Hurricane Beulah]], also tend to make good rainmakers.<ref>{{cite report |author=Roth, David M |url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/txhur.pdf |title=Texas Hurricane History |chapter=A Brief Climatology of Tropical Cyclones in Texas |accessdate=June 6, 2012 |archivedate=June 6, 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68E1tE0B0?url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/txhur.pdf |author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center |publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service |df= }}</ref> Slow moving systems, such as [[Tropical Storm Amelia (1978)|Tropical Storm Amelia]] or [[Hurricane Harvey]] also can produce significant rainfall over Texas. Harvey's storm total rainfall is the most recorded within the United States.<ref name="Harvey"/><ref>{{cite web|title=The previous record for total rainfall during a tropical cyclone has been broken|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?dir=next&pil=PNSHGX&e=201708291411|publisher=National Weather Service Houston/Galveston TX|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> Harvey's extremely heavy rainfall produced catastrophic flooding across much of southeastern Texas; particularly in and around the [[Houston metropolitan area]], where accumulations exceeded {{convert|40|in|mm|abbr=on}} over a four-day period.<ref name="Harvey">{{cite report|author=Lixion Avila|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=August 29, 2017|title=Tropical Storm Harvey Advisory Number 38|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2017/al09/al092017.public.038.shtml|location=Miami, Florida}}</ref> [[Tropical Storm Claudette (1979)|Tropical Storm Claudette]] holds the national 24-hour rainfall record for the United States, with {{convert|42|in|mm}} falling within a day.<ref name="Claudette">{{cite book|author=Roth, David M|author2=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|title=Tropical Cyclone Point Maxima|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service|chapter=Tropical Storm Claudette|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/claudette1979.html|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>
