==Utah== On occasion, [[Utah]] is impacted by the remnants of eastern Pacific tropical cyclones. The remains of [[1982 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Olivia|Olivia]] moved through the region in 1982, spurring spotty moderate to heavy rainfall exceeding {{convert|7|in|mm}} in isolated spots.<ref name="Western"/> [[File:Hurricane Olivia Sep 21 1982 1830Z.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Olivia 1982]] <!--Using wpc rainfall data only--> {| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=in Utah}} |- | 1 || 188.2 || 7.41 || [[1982 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Olivia|Olivia 1982]] || Cottonwood Weir ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 2 || 109.5 || 4.31 || [[1977 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Doreen|Doreen 1977]] || [[Logan, Utah|Logan 5 SW Experimental Farm]] ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 3 || 61.7 || 2.43 || [[Hurricane Javier (2004)|Javier 2004]] || [[Monticello, Utah|Monticello 15 ESE]] ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 4 || 59.4 || 2.34 || [[1990 Pacific hurricane season#Hurricane Boris|Boris 1990]] || Bartholomew Powerhouse ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 5 || 56.1 || 2.21 || [[Hurricane Nora (1997)|Nora 1997]] || [[Enterprise, Utah|Enterprise]] ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 6 || 48.0 || 1.89 || [[Hurricane Lester (1992)|Lester 1992]] || [[Cedar City, Utah|Cedar City]] and [[New Harmony, Utah|New Harmony]] ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 7 || 38.6 || 1.52 || [[Hurricane Isis (1998)|Isis 1998]] || [[La Verkin, Utah|La Verkin]] ||<ref name="Western"/> |- | 8 || 33.8 || 1.33 || [[Hurricane Kathleen (1976)|Kathleen 1976]] || [[New Harmony, Utah|New Harmony]] ||<ref name="Western"/> |- |} {{clear}}
==Vermont== A large swath over heavy rainfall spread up the East Coast along a frontal zone draped over the northern side of [[Hurricane Floyd]].<ref name="FLOYD"/> Over {{convert|11|in|mm}} fell across portions of [[Vermont]], the most recorded during the passage of a tropical cyclone or its remnants within the state.<ref name="New Eng"/> [[File:Erin 1995-08-03 1359Z.png|thumb|right|250 px|Hurricane Erin]] {| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=in Vermont}} |- | 1 || 292.9 || 11.53 || [[Hurricane Floyd|Floyd 1999]] || Mount Mansfield ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |- | 2 || 285.2 || 11.23 || [[Hurricane Irene|Irene 2011]] || Mendon ||<ref name="Irene2011PA37"/> |- | 3 || 209.8 || 8.26 || [[Hurricane Connie|Connie 1955]] || [[Whitingham, Vermont|Whitingham 1 W]] ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |- | 4 || 170.2 || 6.70 || [[Hurricane Erin (1995)|Erin 1995]] || Morrisville Stowe State Park ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |- | 5 || 167.9 || 6.61 || [[Tropical Storm Lee (2011)|Lee 2011]] || Pownal ||<ref name="lee2011"/> |- | 6 || 160.8 || 6.33 || [[Hurricane Donna|Donna 1960]] || [[Somerset, Vermont|Somerset]] ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |- | 7 || 145.5 || 5.73 || [[Hurricane Bertha (1996)|Bertha 1996]] || [[Dorset, Vermont|Dorset 2 SE]] ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |- | 8 || 126.5 || 4.98 || [[Tropical Storm Chris (1988)|Chris 1988]] || [[Vernon, Vermont|Vernon]] ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |- | 9 || 124.7 || 4.91 || [[Hurricane Eloise|Eloise 1975]] || [[Vernon, Vermont|Vernon]] ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |- | 10 || 113.7 || 4.48 || [[Hurricane Able (1950)|Able 1950]] || Searsburg Power Plant ||<ref name="New Eng"/> |}
==Virginia== Virginia has some special considerations that affect tropical cyclone-related rainfall. Mountains to the west act as a perfect mechanism for upward motion during sustained east winds, which can lead to flash flooding and landslides in that region (e.g. [[Hurricane Camille]]). As a tropical system approaches from the south, a frontal zone sets up between the moist Atlantic Ocean and the drier landmass to the west. This boundary can set up two or three days in advance of a tropical storm, and can lead up to prolonged heavy rains across coastal sections (e.g. [[Hurricane Floyd]]). As the cyclone advances north, the boundary will slowly shift west, but progresses west of a [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]]/[[Washington, D.C.]] line.<ref name="Virginia history">{{cite book|author=Roth, David M|author2=Cobb, Hugh|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/roth/vaclimohur.htm|title=Virginia Hurricane History|chapter=Virginia Tropical Cyclone Climatology|accessdate=June 6, 2012|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service}}</ref> [[File:Camilleaugust201969.png|thumb|right|Camille impacting Virginia on August&nbsp;20, 1969.]] {| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=in Virginia}} |- | 1 || 685.8 || 27.00 || [[Hurricane Camille|Camille 1969]] || West-Central Nelson County ||<ref name="Mid Atl"/> |- | 2 || 532.4 || 20.96 || [[Tropical Storm Lee (2011)|Lee 2011]] || Colonial Beach ||<ref name="Lee 11">{{cite report|url={{NHC TCR url|id=AL132011_Lee}}|title=Tropical Storm Lee|author2=National Hurricane Center|author=Brown, Daniel P|date=December 15, 2011|accessdate=June 1, 2012|format=PDF|pages=20–25|type=Tropical Cyclone Report|publisher=United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Weather Service}}</ref> |- | 3 || 513.1 || 20.20 || [[Hurricane Isabel|Isabel 2003]] || Upper Sherando ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 4 || 480.1 || 18.9 || [[1942 Atlantic hurricane season#Tropical Storm Eight|October 1942 T.S.]] || Big Meadows ||<ref name="Rain pre 50s"/> |- | 5 || 457.2 || 18.0 || [[Hurricane Ida (2009)|Ida 2009]] || [[Hampton, Virginia|Hampton 1.8 NW]] ||<ref name="Mid Atl"/> |- | 6 || 444.5 || 17.50 || [[1940 South Carolina hurricane|Southeast hurricane 1940]] || [[Keysville, Virginia|Keysville]] ||<ref name="Rain pre 50s"/> |- | 7 || 431.3 || 16.98 || [[Hurricane Floyd|Floyd 1999]] || [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg 2 N]] ||<ref name="Mid Atl"/> |- | 8 || 406.4 || 16.00 || [[Hurricane Fran|Fran 1996]] || Big Meadows ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 9 || 364.0 || 14.33 || [[Hurricane Cleo|Cleo 1964]] || Back Bay Wildlife Refuge ||<ref name="WPCMAX"/> |- | 10 || 360.9 || 14.21 || [[Hurricane Matthew|Matthew 2016]] || [[Chesapeake, Virginia|Chesapeake]] || <ref name="Matthew 16"/> |}
==Washington== Impacts from tropical cyclones in the [[Pacific Northwest]] are rare.<ref name="Western"/> The remains of [[1997 Pacific hurricane season#Tropical Storm Ignacio|Ignacio]] moved through the region, spurring spotty moderate rainfall across the region.<ref name="IG"/> [[Image:Tropical storm ignacio (1997).JPG|thumb|right|250 px|Ignacio (1997)]] {| class="wikitable" {{Wettest tropical cyclones start|Country=in Washington}} |- | 1 || 18.3 || 0.72 || [[Tropical Storm Ignacio (1997)|Ignacio 1997]] || Merwin Dam ||<ref name="Western"/> |- |} {{clear}}
==West Virginia== Although Hurricane Agnes was barely a hurricane at landfall in [[Florida]], its major impact was over the Mid-Atlantic region, where Agnes combined with a non-tropical low to produce widespread heavy rainfall, including amounts approaching {{convert|8|in|mm}} in isolated spots of [[West Virginia]].<ref name="Mid Atl"/> These rains produced widespread severe flooding from [[Virginia]] northward to New York, with other flooding occurring over the western portions of the Carolinas. [[Image:Hurricane Frances 05 sept 2004 1815Z.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|Hurricane Frances (2004)]]
